        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&REPLY_ID=60198&TOPIC_ID=7484&FORUM_ID=1&CAT_ID=1&Forum_Title=General+Discussions&Topic_Title=Dots+and+Boss+Mobs&M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>


        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2">If you want a yes-no answer, sorry can't provide that. :(  That's kinda why I just posted the patch message, it's the only factual information we have and you can draw your own conclusions.  (Unless Verant has fessed up)  For the unfactual (ie, BS, don't believe it) part, me and a druid discussed this at length eons ago and came up with:</P><P>It's saying:</P><P>Mob moves less than 18 seconds = does more damage than pre-path<BR>Mob moves exactly 18 seconds = does same pre-patch<BR>Mob moves more than 18 seconds = does less than pre-patch</P><P>Inferring from this, the dot damages were increased enough so that 66% of of 18 seconds would equate to the pre-patch dot.  If it was being kited longer, the 66% hit would apply to more ticks.  The penalty is applied at the tick, if the mob is moving.</P><P>If mobs' position has a movement vector, then it'd be safe to say that knocking the mob with melee around won't be considered movement.  If it doesn't, and loc's are checked before and at the tick (which is very likely since that's how channeling works), then it's possible through chance to make the mob appear to be chasing you at the tick; and you'd get a 66% hit on that one tick.  In this case, staying on the same side as the bulk of the melees pushing the mob (tho they should surround it unless pushing on purpose so there's no movement) will mimic the mob running away from you...unless the mob orientation is checked also, in which case you can turn around 180 degrees from where you stand.  It's cheesy but if you knockback a mob while facing away from it, it will push the mob towards you.</P><P>Bottom line: Unless the mob is being kited or is moving continuously throughout the duration of your dot (more than the sporatic jumps that melees push mobs with), you'll do more than 2/3 damage.  It's possible that you'd be doing full damage anyway: 1) if there is a movement vector checked (where a mob was/is vs where a mob is/wants-to-be), 2) if there's a large threshhold that's considered movement. ie, moving three paces isn't considered movement worth penalizing, moving eight paces (like a snared mob chasing you), would.  From the 'If the monster is in melee with you, there is no change to how a DoT spell works.' line, it sounds like this may be the case.</P><P>Sorry if this makes no sense.  Need more caffeine.</P><P>edit: if I didn't make it clear in the rambling above, there is NO timer that says 'woops 18 seconds up, healing this mob 33% of the dot damage taken'.  The 66% hit happens at each individual, separate tick that the mob is moving, as the patch message says.  The 18 seconds is the time where you cross the threshold of how much damage the dot did before and after patch.</P><P>Edited by - orwen on 10/06/2001  09:30:53<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
